body:
I was working on some code which here is a minimized equivalent: ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=f6bcb9831f819220401cdae0576340fc))
```rust
fn main() {
    let x: Box<dyn Iterator<Item = Box<dyn Iterator<Item = i32>>>>;
    x = Box::new(iter::once(Box::new(iter::empty())));
}
```
Which doesn't compile:
```
error[[E0271]](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/error-index.html#E0271): type mismatch resolving `<std::iter::Once<Box<std::iter::Empty<_>>> as Iterator>::Item == Box<dyn Iterator<Item = i32>>`
 [--> src/main.rs:5:9
](https://play.rust-lang.org/#)  |
5 |     x = Box::new(iter::once(Box::new(iter::empty())));
  |         ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ expected trait object `dyn Iterator`, found struct `std::iter::Empty`
  |
  = note: expected struct `Box<dyn Iterator<Item = i32>>`
             found struct `Box<std::iter::Empty<_>>`
  = note: required for the cast to the object type `dyn Iterator<Item = Box<dyn Iterator<Item = i32>>>`
```
At first I thought it is a compiler bug/limitation, but after reading about type coercions, it seems like it is working as intended. It would be great if compiler suggest adding an `as _` here:
```rust
fn main() {
    let x: Box<dyn Iterator<Item = Box<dyn Iterator<Item = i32>>>>;
    x = Box::new(iter::once(Box::new(iter::empty()) as _));
}
```
